When I was a correspondent for a Jewish newspaper, I normally observed
Shabbat at home. But my editor told me it was important to cover a speech on
a Friday night at an Orthodox shul and nobody was available to report on
this emergency meeting. I agreed to take the assignment only because the
message was so important to the Jewish community.

I managed to get a seat close to the speaker and turned on my miniature tape
recorder when he began to speak. I thought nobody saw me, because the device
is no larger than a ball point pen and I carried it in my breast pocket,
under my jacket.

After the speech, at the Oneg Shabbat, an elderly man approached me. Wearing
a black hat with a wide brim and a beard, he spoke with a European accent.
&quot;You're from the paper, aren't you?&quot; he asked. I told him I was. &quot;You taped
the speech, didn't you?&quot; he asked. I admitted I had. &quot;You drove here, didn't
you?&quot; he asked. Again I didn't lie. &quot;Are you parked nearby?&quot; he asked and I
told him my car was on the next block. &quot;Then maybe you wouldn't mind taking
me home?&quot; he asked. I laughed and we left together.

I am sure G-d forgave him, and I hope G-d forgave me, because he really
couldn't walk. I asked him what he would have done if I hadn't been there
and he said there was always someone who drove.

Leon
