My mom, who lived at one time in a city in upstate New York, mentions
that the city's large orthodox synagogue's parking lot was open on
Saturdays, and the large Conservative synagogue's was closed.  Of
course, people drove to both synagogues -- not-as-religious-as-perhaps-
they-should-have-been orthodox and not-as-religious-as-perhaps-they-
should-have-been Conservative people, respectively -- and the rabbis
of both synagogues were against driving on Saturdays.  But the
orthodox place accommodated drivers, is all, while the Conservative
did not.  The reason, if I recall correctly, that my mom gave was that
the orthodox place sought driving congregants who would otherwise go
elsewhere or nowhere.

Michael Hamm
